{
  "name": "Work on GitHub Issue",
  "version": "2.3.0",
  "description": "Fetches open issues from the current GitHub repository, lets the user pick one, and then guides the agent through implementing it using the correct Kiro spec workflow based on issue type. Posts progress updates as comments on the issue throughout execution. After implementation, invokes the DevOps-Engineer to create a deployment plan for user approval before executing. Posts a final summary comment tracking completed and outstanding work. Closes the issue when all work is complete.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "The user wants to work on a GitHub issue. Follow this workflow exactly:\n\n## Step 1: Fetch Issues\n\n1. Determine the current repository's GitHub owner and repo name from `git remote -v`.\n2. Use the GitHub MCP tools to list open issues for this repository, sorted by creation date descending (most recent first), limited to 10.\n3. If there are NO open issues, tell the user there are no open issues and stop.\n\n## Step 2: Present Issues to the User\n\n- If there is exactly ONE open issue: display its title, number, and a brief summary of the body. Ask the user: \"This is the only open issue. Would you like me to work on this?\"\n- If there are MULTIPLE open issues: display the 10 most recently created issues as a numbered list showing `#<number> — <title>`. Ask the user to pick one by number. After the user picks one, fetch the full issue details (title, body, labels, comments) and display them. Then ask: \"Would you like me to work on this issue?\"\n\n## Step 3: Wait for Confirmation\n\nDo NOT proceed until the user explicitly confirms they want you to work on the selected issue. If the user says no or picks a different issue, go back to the selection step.\n\n## Step 4: Classify the Issue Type\n\nOnce the user confirms, determine the issue type from its labels, title, and body:\n\n- **Bug**: The issue describes something broken, incorrect, or behaving unexpectedly. Look for labels like `bug`, or language describing incorrect behaviour, errors, crashes, or regressions.\n- **Feature or Task**: The issue describes new functionality, an enhancement, a refactoring task, or any work that is not a bug fix. This includes labels like `enhancement`, `feature`, `task`, or any issue that is not a bug.\n\nThe issue type determines which Kiro spec workflow to use. This is non-negotiable.\n\n## Step 5: Assess Complexity\n\nAssess the complexity of the issue:\n\n### Very Simple\nThe change is obvious, localised to one or two files, and requires no design decisions. Examples: fixing a typo, updating a version number, adding a single field, renaming something.\n\n- You MUST tell the user: \"This looks like a very simple change. I can implement it directly without creating a spec. Are you happy for me to proceed in vibe-coding mode?\"\n- Only proceed with direct implementation if the user explicitly agrees.\n- If the user says no, treat it as Simple instead.\n\n### Simple\nWell-defined and self-contained but involves enough work that a plan is useful. Examples: adding a new small feature, fixing a bug with a clear root cause, refactoring a single module.\n\n- Create a spec directory under `.kiro/specs/` named after the issue.\n- Create ALL THREE spec files in a single pass, then present the full spec to the user for review.\n- For bugs: create `bugfix.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md` together.\n- For features/tasks: create `requirements.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md` together.\n- Ask: \"Here is the full spec. Would you like to refine anything, or shall I proceed with implementation?\"\n- Iterate if the user requests changes. Once confirmed, implement all tasks.\n\n### Complex\nLarge, ambiguous, has multiple possible approaches, or spans many files/modules. Examples: adding a major feature, redesigning a subsystem, implementing a new workflow.\n\n- Create a spec directory under `.kiro/specs/` named after the issue.\n- Follow the FULL spec-driven development workflow with user confirmation at each stage.\n- The first file depends on the issue type (see Step 6). Present it and wait for confirmation before proceeding to the next file.\n\n## Step 6: Execute the Correct Spec Workflow\n\nThe spec workflow is determined by the issue type from Step 4. You MUST use the correct workflow.\n\n### For Bug Issues: Bugfix Spec Workflow\n\nBugs ALWAYS use the Bugfix Spec workflow. The first file is `bugfix.md`, not `requirements.md`.\n\n`bugfix.md` must capture:\n- **Current Behavior (Defect)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system [incorrect behavior]\n- **Expected Behavior (Correct)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system SHALL [correct behavior]\n- **Unchanged Behavior (Regression Prevention)**: WHEN [condition] THEN the system SHALL CONTINUE TO [existing behavior]\n\nWorkflow order: `bugfix.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`\n\nFor Simple bugs: create all three files at once, present for review, then implement.\nFor Complex bugs: create `bugfix.md` first, get confirmation, then `design.md`, get confirmation, then `tasks.md`, get confirmation, then implement.\n\n### For Feature or Task Issues: Requirements-First Workflow\n\nFeatures and tasks ALWAYS use the Requirements-First workflow. The first file is `requirements.md`.\n\n`requirements.md` must capture requirements using EARS notation:\n- WHEN [condition/event] THE SYSTEM SHALL [expected behavior]\n\nWorkflow order: `requirements.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`\n\nFor Simple features/tasks: create all three files at once, present for review, then implement.\nFor Complex features/tasks: create `requirements.md` first, get confirmation, then `design.md`, get confirmation, then `tasks.md`, get confirmation, then implement.\n\n## Sub-Agent Collaboration\n\nYou do not work alone. Use the following sub-agents to produce higher-quality specs and implementation:\n\n- **Solutions-Architect** (`/Solutions-Architect`): Invoke this sub-agent when designing spec files. The Solutions Architect researches the codebase, evaluates architectural options, and produces well-reasoned design decisions. Use it to:\n  - Help draft `design.md` with architecture recommendations and tradeoff analysis.\n  - Research the current codebase and existing patterns before proposing changes.\n  - Evaluate whether the issue requires changes in other repositories (cross-repo impact).\n  - Review `requirements.md` or `bugfix.md` for completeness and feasibility.\n\n- **DevOps-Engineer** (`/DevOps-Engineer`): Invoke this sub-agent when the issue involves infrastructure, deployment, CI/CD, CloudFormation, CDK, or pipeline changes. The DevOps Engineer implements infrastructure changes through GitOps. Use it to:\n  - Help draft `tasks.md` for infrastructure-related implementation steps.\n  - Validate CloudFormation templates or CDK code during implementation.\n  - Troubleshoot deployment failures if implementation triggers pipeline issues.\n  - Advise on operational concerns in `design.md` (monitoring, rollback, permissions).\n  - **Produce a Deployment Plan section in `design.md`** (see below).\n\nWhen creating spec files, actively consult these sub-agents rather than working in isolation. The Solutions Architect should inform the design, and the DevOps Engineer should inform any infrastructure or operational tasks.\n\n### Deployment Plan in design.md\n\nWhen producing `design.md` for ANY spec (whether Simple or Complex, bug or feature), you MUST invoke the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent (`/DevOps-Engineer`) to produce a **Deployment Plan** section within the design document. This is in ADDITION to the post-implementation deployment planning in Step 7 — the design should already contain the deployment approach before implementation begins.\n\nThe Deployment Plan section in `design.md` must cover:\n- **What needs to be deployed**: Which artifacts, services, or resources will change.\n- **How it should be deployed**: The deployment mechanism (pipeline, GitOps, manual steps).\n- **Infrastructure changes**: Any CloudFormation, CDK, Terraform, or other IaC changes required.\n- **Pipeline considerations**: Whether CI/CD pipelines need modification, new stages, or new triggers.\n- **Rollback strategy**: How to revert the change if something goes wrong post-deployment.\n\nThis ensures deployment concerns are considered during design, not as an afterthought.\n\n## Step 7: Deployment Planning\n\nAfter implementation is complete (all tasks done, tests passing, linting clean), you MUST run a deployment planning phase before considering the work finished.\n\n1. **Invoke the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent** (`/DevOps-Engineer`) and ask it to create a deployment plan for the changes just implemented. Provide it with:\n   - The issue number and title.\n   - A summary of what was changed (files modified, new resources, config changes).\n   - The spec directory path so it can review the design and tasks.\n   - Any infrastructure or pipeline files that were created or modified.\n\n2. **Present the deployment plan to the user.** Display the full plan clearly and ask: \"Here is the deployment plan. Would you like to refine anything, or shall I proceed with deployment?\"\n\n3. **Wait for explicit user confirmation.** Do NOT proceed with deployment until the user confirms they are happy with the plan. If the user requests changes, iterate on the plan with the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent and re-present it.\n\n4. **Execute the deployment.** Once the user confirms, invoke the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent again to execute the deployment plan. The DevOps-Engineer will make the necessary infrastructure changes through GitOps (editing CloudFormation templates, CDK code, pipeline configurations, etc.) and guide the user through commit, push, and deployment tracking.\n\n5. If the changes are purely application code with no infrastructure or deployment implications, tell the user: \"These changes are application-level only and don't require a separate deployment plan. They will be deployed through the standard pipeline on merge.\" Then ask the user to confirm this is acceptable.\n\n## Step 8: Close the Issue\n\nAfter ALL work is complete — implementation done, tests passing, deployment executed or confirmed unnecessary — you MUST close the GitHub issue.\n\n1. Post the final summary comment (see Work Tracking section) with Outstanding set to \"None — all work complete.\"\n2. Use the `gh` CLI to close the issue: `gh issue close <issue_number> --repo <owner>/<repo> --reason completed`.\n3. Tell the user the issue has been closed.\n\nIf work is NOT fully complete (outstanding tasks, pending deployments, manual actions required), do NOT close the issue. Instead, post the final summary comment with the outstanding items and leave the issue open for the next session.\n\n## Rules\n\n1. NEVER skip the issue selection and confirmation steps.\n2. NEVER start implementation without the user confirming the approach.\n3. For very simple tasks, you MUST get explicit permission for vibe-coding mode.\n4. Bug issues MUST use the Bugfix Spec workflow (`bugfix.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`). NEVER create `requirements.md` for a bug.\n5. Feature and task issues MUST use the Requirements-First workflow (`requirements.md` → `design.md` → `tasks.md`). NEVER create `bugfix.md` for a feature or task.\n6. If you are unsure about complexity, default to the Simple approach.\n7. If you are unsure whether an issue is a bug or feature, ask the user.\n8. Reference the issue number in commit messages when making changes.\n9. Consult the Solutions-Architect sub-agent when drafting spec files, especially `design.md`.\n10. Consult the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent when the issue involves infrastructure, deployment, or pipeline changes.\n11. NEVER skip the deployment planning phase (Step 7) after implementation is complete.\n12. NEVER execute a deployment without explicit user confirmation of the deployment plan.\n13. ALWAYS post progress comments on the GitHub issue as described in the Progress Reporting section.\n14. ALWAYS post a final summary comment on the issue when finishing a session, as described in the Work Tracking section.\n15. ALWAYS include a Deployment Plan section in `design.md` produced by the DevOps-Engineer sub-agent.\n16. When ALL work is complete, ALWAYS close the GitHub issue. When work is outstanding, NEVER close the issue.\n\n## Progress Reporting via Issue Comments\n\nThroughout your execution, you MUST post progress updates as comments on the GitHub issue you are working on. Use the GitHub MCP tools to add comments to the issue. This keeps stakeholders informed and creates an audit trail.\n\n### When to Post Comments\n\n1. **When starting work**: Post a comment saying work has begun and outline your plan (e.g. issue type classification, complexity assessment, and the approach you will take).\n2. **At key milestones**: Post a comment when you reach significant checkpoints:\n   - Spec created (requirements/bugfix, design, tasks files written).\n   - Implementation started.\n   - Tests passing.\n   - Linting clean.\n   - Deployment plan created.\n   - Deployment confirmed/executed.\n3. **When encountering blockers or errors**: Post a comment describing the problem, what you tried, and what you need to proceed. This ensures visibility even if the session is interrupted.\n\n### Comment Format\n\nKeep comments concise and structured. Example:\n\n```\n🚀 **Work started** — Classified as a Feature (Simple complexity). Plan: create spec → implement → deploy.\n```\n\n```\n✅ **Milestone: Spec complete** — Created `requirements.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md` under `.kiro/specs/issue-name/`. Awaiting user confirmation to proceed with implementation.\n```\n\n```\n⚠️ **Blocker** — Tests failing due to missing dependency `foo`. Investigating.\n```\n\n## Work Tracking: Completed and Outstanding\n\nWhen you finish your current session (whether the task is fully complete or not), you MUST post a **final summary comment** on the GitHub issue. This comment serves as a handoff record so that any future agent picking up the issue knows exactly where things stand.\n\n### Final Summary Comment Must Include\n\n1. **What has been completed**:\n   - List of tasks/steps finished (spec files created, code implemented, tests passing, etc.).\n   - Files created or modified.\n   - Any deployments that were executed successfully.\n\n2. **What is still outstanding**:\n   - Remaining tasks from `tasks.md` that have not been implemented.\n   - Deployment steps still required.\n   - Manual actions needed (e.g. user needs to configure secrets, approve a pipeline, etc.).\n   - Known issues or blockers that were not resolved.\n\n3. **Next steps**: A clear statement of what the next agent (or the user) should do to continue.\n\n### Example Final Summary Comment\n\n```\n📋 **Session Summary**\n\n**Completed:**\n- Created spec: `.kiro/specs/add-auth-module/requirements.md`, `design.md`, `tasks.md`\n- Implemented tasks 1.1.1 through 1.2.3\n- All tests passing (98% coverage)\n- Linting clean\n\n**Outstanding:**\n- Task 1.3.1: Deploy CloudFormation stack for Cognito user pool\n- Task 1.3.2: Update pipeline config to include auth integration tests\n- Manual action: User must add `COGNITO_CLIENT_SECRET` to SSM Parameter Store\n\n**Next steps:** Invoke DevOps-Engineer to execute the deployment plan. User must commit and push current changes first.\n```\n\nThis comment MUST be posted even if the task is fully complete (in which case the Outstanding section simply says \"None — all work complete.\" and the issue will be closed — see Step 8)."
  }
}
